Somebody asked me yesterday when I began fully embracing my creativity. Funny thing is, until I started IG almost 8 years ago, I never would have described myself as creative. I had categories for creatives and they mostly fell into the artist category. And, yep, I never considered myself an artist. I've been told to look back at your earliest, most satisfying experiences as a child to identify what it is that you should be doing more of as an adult. I asked that question about 8 years ago. And the memories that cropped up were related to creating. Like the one Halloween my bestie and I found a huge refrigerator box and created a human-sized VW bug (our favorite car at the time). I guess that's when I realized I was born to create even though I can't paint or sculpt. I came across this definition today: artists have the desire and ability to envision, design and fabricate images, objects, and structures we encounter, use, occupy and enjoy every day of our lives. Framed like that, I think we are all artists. We are all made to create in unique ways. And it explains my compulsion at Christmas to decorate. I wanted to create an ethereal, magical moment in the hallway. It's where I look out from my desk. It's where we pass through to use the bathroom and go to bed. Even the everyday moments ought to be beautiful. Happy Tuesday, friends. Tell me, do you consider yourself an artist?

A few days ago, I came across a listing on Facebook Marketplace for "African folk art." The only pic was a close-up of beads applied to a surface. I could tell by the beading and the gold grout that it was likely a turn-of-the-century memoryware piece. The guy took a few days to respond. But when he did, I jumped on it, knowing very little about its size. But I was certain that for the listed price whatever it was it would be worth it. I picked it up today and was astounded by its size and perfect condition. I've seen a ton of memoryware, but nothing quite this elaborate. The guy also tossed in a memoryware lamp by the same artist. I think I'm going to work on incorporating this piece into my holiday decor, because, why not? It's sparkly and festive! I guess the moral of the story is to always look beyond the description and the bad photos. There might be incredible treasure awaiting.

You're likely familiar with the word "schadenfreude"--the delight in someone's misery. But have you heard of "freudenfreude"? It means to delight in another's success. There was a period during my early IG days when I failed miserably at freudenfreude. Those days my dreams felt like they were on permanent pause and everyone else's dreams were fast-tracking: a blown up account, a magazine feature, a book deal, a TV show, a new home, a new thing  When you want something badly and someone else gets that thing, freudenfreude is a discipline. You must practice it The deeper your desire, the more of a discipline it is. The more you must choose it.  I'm not perfect at freudenfreude. But I want more of it in my life. Because the opposite makes me miserable. Withholding joy doesn't change my circumstances. It only ruins my peace. It means I'm choosing myself over relationship with others. And that goes against the very core of who I want to be. May 2023 be the Year of Freudenfreude. How about we kick it off and share in the joy of someone's success in the comments below? L start!  I'm thrilled for  Natalie of @home_ec_op and her new show on Magnolia. I love seeing Abby of  @adventuresinabbyland
bring her colorful and pattern filled home to life. I love watching @once.upon.an.italianate and @dawnhenriandgeorge bring their italianates to life. I loved watching @vintageholiday share his home on HGTV. There's so much more joy to spread. I hope you join me below. #holidaycheer #vintagechristmas #christmasjoy #vintagedecor #vintageholidaydecor #vintagechristmasdecorations

I got a bee in my bonnet and decided to make my own wrapping paper this year. I was growing tired of my previous looks. I bought a giant roll of craft paper from Amazon and some acrylic paints from Michael's. My original idea was to doodle. But who am I kidding? I can't draw. I gave up, halved the paper to absorb the paint and throw it away. And by chance, I opened it up, and it had created the most abstract-ish type of painting. So I just kept adding splatters of paint to the base piece and laid another piece on top. And that's how this paper was created. By failure.
Of course, the best part, are the vintage doodads atop. People have been sending me images of their blinged up packages, inspired by last year. And that makes me so happy. (Yes...I try to reuse. Yes, people keep what's on top of they want it. Most of these are for family.)

Hello new followers and old friends! It seems my holiday home tour drew a new crowd. And it's been a while since I've shown my face and shared some terribly uninteresting facts about myself...but facts nonetheless that tell you a bit about the person behind the pics.
1. Yesterday I shared a car selfie in Stories. I posted it without hesitation, and then realized after I posted it how deep my laugh lines are getting. I have been working on accepting this aging thing over the past few years, and yesterday I chose to say to myself, "Those wrinkles are sexy." (Not sure I'm feeling it today. But it was a start.)
2. I'm wearing faux leather pants here. They're probably too tight. But along with accepting my wrinkles, I'm trying to accept my body. I worked out a ton over the past year. And I've recently been thinking about my perception of my body isn't the reality. I've worked hard for a relatively fit body. And I think it's time to celebrate that in some pleather.
3. This feels more like a confession than a fun fact, but I watch "Sister Wives." It's the only reality TV I watch. There are a million reasons not to watch it that I seem to ignore.
4. I can't eat sushi, bananas, yogurt, cottage cheese, pudding, and a variety of other foods with an odd texture. Just can't do it. 
5. I hide things in our house. Not on purpose. But I hate visual clutter. So things that are really important to someone else I put in a place that someone else would never think to look. Lots of hide and seek around here. But I don't think anyone really likes the game. 😂

Thanks to all of you for sticking around here. Showing up with kindness. I hope to get to know many more of you in the year to come!

I signed up for Instagram 8 years ago on New Years day. I've posted over 3100 times since then. (And that doesn't include Stories or the posts I've since deleted.) I like to think back to my joining day. It was a vectoring moment. There was so much I didn't know--about the world and, more importantly, about myself. There's the obvious stuff I was clueless about, like how to style an image for a square and take a decent picture (I probably spent an unnecessary hour on this shot). I didn't know what a stylist was exactly or what working for a magazine really looked like. I didn't know how important cultivating my creativity was, either. I suppose that's what IG has been for me. One giant Master Class on living a creative life. Of course, part of the course has been about dealing with self-doubt, especially when faced with rejection. There have also been a few lessons on discontent and what to do with it. Then there have been the lessons on the importance of community. The lessons really have been endless... And I like to think that where I am today, and all the good things I've experienced in my creative life, are because of IG. So while I know IG won't be around forever (maybe not even for 8 more years. Who knows?!), I'm so grateful you're here and for the many ways you've shaped my creative life.

Let's talk about changes for this room in 2023, which I've been thinking about for some time.

1. Change out the drapes this spring to a floral or another pattern. These are nice. I actually love them. They're classic. My mother-in-law slaved to make them for me. But after 20 years, I am craving change. And when I look at all my saved posts and pins, one consistent characteristic is patterned drapes.
2. That brown chinoiserie chair in the corner. I love it. It was a thrift store find and helped round out this room 8 years ago. But it feels small, especially with the addition of the sofa. And it's so brown in this room, which has so much brown. I want a larger chair recovered in a fabric with more pinks and greens and blues and yellows (thanks Pinterest again for showing me this!).
3. After 3 years of my husband working from home in that chaise lounge, it needs to be recovered. Desperately. I think I'll go with a true velvet this time. Though I have toyed with the idea of doing a pattern.
4. For now the Lee Woodard rocker is staying. Since moving it away from the gold cabinet, I actually sit in it now. But, nobody else does. So, who knows, maybe that will get replaced eventually too.
5. A larger rug. I actually don't mind the colors of this one. But it's about 3 feet short on width, and 4 to 5 feet short on length. This room is tricky because of how narrow it is, and because it bleeds into the dining room. The rug is tricky.
6. Finally, I want to  paint that front door the color of the walls. I hate how it breaks up this wall. I know it's a controversial move. But I can always strip it if it doesn't work.

I never thought I'd write an entire post about collecting and Economics 101. Lately, there's been a trend toward decorating with original art—folk art, paintings, sculpture, furniture. Everyone--not just the hardcore collector-- wants something unique to reflect how unique they are. It's a pendulum swing away from mass produced and disposable. But unique by definition is rare. That creates an imbalance of supply and demand. Less supply and more demand? Dealers have permission to hike up prices. Creating a collection of rare items takes time—and money. My tramp art box collection is a slow grow: on average one new piece a year, based on the style I like and the price I can afford. It’s no wonder we often get our start collecting less rare, less expensive items. In fact, that’s how most of my collections have taken shape over the years. I found my first of these Chinese jade flower candleholders at Goodwill for 99 cents. That was about six years ago. It was sculptural, and the colors fit my aesthetic. A few weeks later I found a couple more for less than a few dollars a piece. Then a friend scored an entire collection for cheap at an auction, which she gifted to me. It grew because the supply was there. Chinese jade wasn’t en vogue six years ago. Fast-forward a few years—the price for these pieces has crept up. I found two more yesterday for $15 a piece. That’s a big jump from 99 cents. But still a bargain when you consider what they’re fetching online (around $75 a piece). I don’t have a hard rule for what I collect. First and foremost, I have to respond to it on an emotional level. I’m likely to grab a piece, however, when it’s absurdly affordable. And often that absurdly affordable piece becomes the cornerstone of a collection.

It took me 3 months to put a  mirror in this frame, partially because I wasn't sure where it would land. I like it here on the front porch. I'm going to pivot for a sec. I've been watching "The Bear." (Why was I so late to this show?) A running theme is that the restaurant biz is a crummy biz to be in. At least if you want to make a decent wage for the amount of effort you put into it. The margin is slim. Yet chefs are willing to take the risk, because of passion and the deeply rooted belief that hospitality and creating a memorable experience matter. (And maybe because they believe they'll be one of the few who makes it big). People often ask for my advice on getting started in the vintage selling biz. I'm such a newbie, and not the greatest business woman. But I am always honest about how it's incredibly difficult to make a living wage doing it. You have to do it because you're passionate about it. Because you believe it matters. And you have to commit to doing it well. The hours you put in are rarely reflected in the profit. In fact, if I actually paid myself and my husband an hourly wage for all the time we pour into Megillicutti, we literally would be making less than minimum wage. Think about that. I realize I'm not the model. There are some people who have cracked the code on profitability. (Help! I need lessons from you!) But I think it's the rarity. I suppose "The Bear" has made me realize I'm a little bit crazy. But I'm definitely not alone.

I called my mom to see if she wanted to join me, binged on peanut butter M& Ms over the weekend (I was at the Extravaganza...seemed like a bad time to start); and Monday said bye-bye to refined sugar and (most) carbs. I'm  also trying to increase my activity--get back to going to OT 4-5 times a week. I'm committing to one month of this. And I'll assess where I am: what's working, what's not. But an early report? Now that I'm actually eating real food, I'm not craving the sugar and simple carbs. Maybe I will as time goes on. (I would call myself a sugar and carb addict, so I'd be surprised if the cravings don't creep in). But right now, I feel satisfied. And motivated. And finally in control. We shall see how the rest of the month goes, as we shall see how many people like the little gold chair in the corner. Crossing my fingers it's all good.
#decoratewithwhatyoulove #antiquepainting #fleamarketdecor #fleamarkeystyle

Shame on me for discounting goldenrod as an ugly weed all these years. Look at it! Next to dahlias, it might be my favorite fall flower. I cut them last night when my friend and I coined a word:glimglob.  The sunset stunned us. (Swipe to see) We anticipated no color because of the heavy cloud cover. It was a moment of unexpected beauty, which would fall under the category of a "glimmer." We hate the word, because, well, it's become a cliche, like "vibe." Another phrase we recently learned from another friend is "joy drop"--when you do something unexpectedly kind for someone. My friend can never remember "drop" and instead says "joy blob," which I amended to "joy glob." Then we put the two together: "glimglob" (reminds me of JibJab). Anyway, this goldenrod is a glimglob, too. I'll be looking for more glimglob. 
#diyflowerarrangement #goldenrod #dahlias #mccoy #mccoypottery

A perfect Saturday in so many ways. I slept in. Drank my coffee in the garden. Cleaned the kitchen. Worked out at OT. Cleaned some more. A humdrum day. But so recharging. And so good to not be on there road questing. (But.... Tomorrow is Elkhorn!)
#stripedsofa #decoratewithwhatyoulove #antiquepainting

This pic will probably look terrible in my gallery. But I don't care, because I want to remember the joy of today--the season closer of Elkhorn. @kooselie and I enjoyed a perfect fall quest. Weather was cool enough for a sweater in the morning. Finds were plentiful. Prices were great. This pic was taken by @kooselie when I retrieved this gaudy folk art Christmas tree, and she set eyes on it the first time. Let's just say we have different styles. (Truth be told, her style is much better than mine.) She was not nearly as enamored with it. But she knew I was. I mean, check out my smile. True story: someone DMed me and said, "I saw that in the back of the dealer's truck, and I thought, 'That's so Megillicutti!'" Indeed, it is. Soooo Megillicutti. #thequestisthebest #antiquingbff #tqitb #vintagejewelrychristmastree #vintagechristmasdecor #elkhornfleamarket #fleamarketdecor #fleamarkeystyle #fleamarketshopping

The Leaning Tower of McCoy Bowls. 
#mccoypotterycollector #mccoy #mccoypottery #collector #collectioncreep #vintagebowls

Art imitating life. Life imitating art.

This painting was tucked away beneath a table at a recent market. It was only $15. (Look high . Look low.) And while my intent was to add this to the "sell" pile, i just couldn't... at least not this month.

#dahliabouquet #antiquepainting #antiqueoilpainting

It's that time of the year when you assess all the things you did wrong in your garden. I learned some valuable lessons about dahlias. I need to stake them earlier and plant the bulbs further apart. In my eagerness to have more variety, I planted them too close together, and many simply didn't thrive. But I have a few that are doing ok, despite their  late start. I'm soaking up every second possible back here before the gloom of fall and winter settle in.

I was 2 seconds from leaving the market this morning. My heart wasn't in it. I wanted to go home and cozy up under the covers. That's always when it seems you find the good stuff. I grabbed all of this art from one dealer...super cheap. I love how they look together. All a little amateur yet saturated. The seascape looks to be of the California coast. The upper left, is of the Snake River in Eastern Oregon (According to the dealer). I typically don't like "guy" portraits, but this  guy is handsome. Glad I dragged myself out of bed and through the entire market.
#antiquing #antiquepainting ##fleamarketshopping #tqitb #thequestisthebest

What's better than stone grapes than stone grapes in a giant clam shell? I desperately want to find a place for this clam shell, but it's feeling impossible in my house. It takes up major real estate. I have this gap in my mind between what is and what I want. In my ideal world, this clam shell filled with alabaster grapes sits atop a table in a grand entry. Dreams are torture, aren't they? 😂  I wanted to welcome all the new followers by way of @amycwhyte, who so graciously posted the brass horse rack I had for sale. It sold immediately. And I wish I had at least 20 more for each person who inquired. Maybe the Quest will reward me again soon. Because that's what I'm here for: the Quest. It is the best! #tqitb #thequestisthebest #alabastercollection #alabastergrapes  #alabasterfruit #collected #collectioncreep

My son admitted one of his friends doesn't think my new pink pleated lampshades in our dining room work. In the current state, she's right. It's because my house is in transition, and I can't make all the changes at once to make it all work together. The drapes really need to change. (I think I got the green light to order custom drapes, right @jerome.at.home ? And those will tie the living and dining room together.) I'm running into the same "in transition" problem in my bedroom. I'm trying to get away from my all-green scheme. I tried adding these pleated drapes (which I picked up over the weekend) to my bedroom. If I keep the drapes (which I need to wash first), I think I'll need to also change the lamps. I'm kind of over the alabaster anyway. So onward the slow decor transition goes--which is how I feel it goes for most of us, though social media might have us think otherwise.
#vintagedecor #slowdecor #slowdecorating #bedroomstyle

Hip-hip-hooray for a rain-free, 70-degree first day of glamping. I still have a bit to do in the interior of the tent. But the picnic area is looking pretty sweet! Last year we hung this shell chandelier in the tent with another chandelier. And it was too much. This year I told @jerome.at.home I wanted to hang it over the table. And I love how it looks. It's so fun to change up the glamping looks a little bit each year. I drew inspiration from this quilt topper I picked up in KY last month. Who else is ready to go glamping? Give it a try. Because the best part of camping truly is decorating. 😂
#glamping #glamp #doorcounty #doorcountywi #peninsulastatepark #camping #letsgocamping

Not much changed this year with the interior of my glamp pad. I had grand visions of using a Victorian fringe floor lamp and my large pair of cloisonne lamps. But all of it was too big for this space. It overwhelmed it. So I stuck with the basics. An antique rug, tole chandelier, alabaster side tables, and a collection of old textiles and thrifted saris. That rug I picked up a few weeks ago in Indiana. It is old and perfectly faded. And was only $150. I was so glad to see it fit this space perfectly. I also deconstructed a Victorian yarn memorial wreath and turned it into a swag. I have yet to figure out how to hang art without poking holes in the tent. That will be a challenge for next year's glamping adventure.
#glamp #glamppad #glamping #letsgoglamping #letsgocamping #prettytent #glampingideas

Last night we drove into the park late, taking a back road to our campground. I looked out the window and spotted a wildly lit up site in the distance and said, "Wow!! That's pretty!" And then I realized it was our site. 😂 (This was kinda the view from the road.)
#glamppad #glampingideas #glamping #peninsulastatepark

My nutrition when I camp is traditionally campish. You know--heavy food. Lots of chips, trail mix, granola bars, cookies, muffins, hot chocolate, candy. We always have peanut butter M&Ms. (I think my husband brought them, but I haven't seen them.) Snacks are everywhere. I realize that apples are not a low carb fruit, but I figured snacking on these would be better than grabbing a handful of candy or a bag of chips.  And they really are delicious. Yes, life is about balance. And I'm prepared to let my regimen slide on occasion. But I want to make it a full month intentionally not eating processed food and sugar. I really want to break my sugar addiction.  But I'll be honest, this weekend has been a challenge. (And let's hear it for a $5 Texasware bowl. I used to find these left and right for under $10...but now they're always $30 or more!)
#camping #glamping #tablescape #falltablescape #honeycrispapple #wisconsinapples #texasware #texasware #greenmccoypottery #mccoypotterycollector #mccoymixingbowl

Victorian yarn art might be one of my favorite things, next to Victorian beadwork.  This was part of a memorial wreath that had seen better days. A few years ago I created a real wreath out of it and used it at Christmas and a year later in my tent. This year, I found it buried in a box and decided to turn it into a swag. It's whimsical, interesting, and textural. I love this addition to the tent this year. In other news, each day in Door County gets colder and colder. I piled on a sheet, a kantha, two down comforters, and two wool blankets... still I was cold. Every night I think about one of my favorite shows, "Naked and Afraid," and have a new appreciation for how impossible the survival conditions are when you're naked, it's raining and it's 48 degrees. Let's just say, I'm not a survivalist (as if my glamping site didn't give that away.) 
#garland #victorianyarnart #folkart #glampingideas #glamping

My lamp situation for glamping this year isn't great. As I mentioned earlier, the pair I pulled from inventory were too big. I spent Thursday trying to find a pair. There was an alabaster pair, but they were pricey. I want sure I could resell them for the marked price. This German porcelain pair is definitely not in my wheelhouse, but they kinda are a nice foil to richer tones in the textiles and rugs. These dahlias I picked up from a grab and go stand. Actually, the gardener was there, and she made a bouquet just for me. We chatted about what it takes to actually sustain a flower biz. And it feels out of my league... At least for now.

Camping in October. Brrrr. Tomorrow night at this time, I'll be snuggled into my real bed. In one layer of clothing. Not 20. 
#glamppad #glamping #peninsulastatepark

Have you ever grown out your bangs? It's a longer-than-desired process. I recovered from a mullet in the seventh grade. And there's always that awkward stage where the bangs aren't long enough to pull back, but if you don't bobby pin them, you're a hot mess. I feel like my home is in that awkward "midway growing out its bangs" stage. That pink hallway was a bold move. And for the past seven months I've been trying to make it make sense with the adjoining rooms, which have lots of green but very little pink. The bedroom is probably the biggest problem. So, I  changed out my lamp to this fringy piece and added a rug with some pops of pink. (I also changed out the curtains, which you can't see). I think it's coming along, even if I'm still in that awkward in-between stage.
#seascapes #seascapepaintings #gallerywall #bedroomdecor #handpaintedmural #handpaintedwall

Some objects deserve their own square. I've had my eye on this lamp for a few years now. I finally purchased it on our way home from Door County. I like the conflict between the tattered silk shade and the decadent fringe. It's that mix of high and low that makes all design work, whether in fashion or interiors, in my opinion.
#antiquelampshade #antiquelamp #vintagelighting

You never know where a Facebook Marketplace pickup will lead. As a dealer, I'm always looking to make the most of one stop. So when someone says they have more stuff I might be interested in, I perk up. Sometimes it's awkward saying, "No, thank you." (Often the stuff is not my taste.) But other times you stumble into some incredible finds, like this antique oil on canvas. The people selling it were helping out an antiques dealer liquidate his estate. He's moving to assisted living and can't keep it all. (Sounds like my future.) They offered a fantastic deal, and I think they felt fantastic selling it to me because my appreciation of it was genuine and effusive. I'm really in love with this piece.
#facebookmarketplacefind #antiquing #antiquepainting #antiqueoilpainting #oiloncanvas #decoratewithwhatyoulove #dealerlife

Too early? Absolutely. But today I'm in Christmas land pricing all the vintage Christmas for the big holiday event at @warehouse55_ next weekend. I've been buying a ton of vintage Christmas. Today I found this whacky tree at an estate sale by @vintagechicagodesign. And sorry to tell you, it's a keeper. But I have sooooooo much cool stuff heading to the shop next week. I can't wait to deck the Elevator. 
#vintagechristmasdecor #vintagechristmas #vintagebottlebrushtree #vintageholiday

Hello! I'm Melissa, the face behind Megillicutti. And it feels like a good time to offer up a few new (not-so) fun facts.
1. I hate purple. Except in sweaters (I guess I'm considered a "winter") and sunsets. I braked for tonight's purple delight on my way home from work.
2. Some people think selling vintage is my full-time job. Nope. I am a writer and editor by day. Dealer by night and weekend. I always feel exhausted trying to sustain both. But the payoff of each is worth it. 
3. Today marks my 4th week not eating sugar or simple carbs.  My mom said my face looks thinner. I don't know. I just know I feel so much better. Last night I splurged and ate some fried cheese curds (bc that's what you do when you are in Wisconsin) and felt sick alllllll night long. My best advice for getting started? Get an accountability partner. @justjudya took the dive with me, and it helped so much to know I wasn't alone.. Also @__hohm__ has provided so much encouragement. Go follow her for regular health tips 
4. I confess. I'm listening to Christmas music. I blame @markalleninspired. 😂 @warehouse55_ is having their annual holiday event this weekend. I have to listen to Christmas music while I price all manner of Christmas doodadery. At least I can justify it.
5. I'm reminding myself today that grey hair is natural at 48. (I see you, spry, wiry flyaway hair!). Today I feel good about aging. Tomorrow may be different. But today? I'm at peace.

Mark your calendar!! This weekend is @warehouse55_ 's Holiday Event! In the past my Christmas inventory has been light. (And I always felt ashamed because the W55 family goes alllll out!) But I'm feeling good about my collection this year. This beaded jewelry art tree is one of a few that will be headed to the shop. I really do love vintage Christmas. It's one of my favorite things to personally collect. Which makes it so difficult to part with. I don't do kitsch or traditional Christmas red, white and green. But I love the pastels, and sparkles, and gold, and wonky homemade stuff. Be sure to drop by this weekend, because if my vibe isn't your vibe, I guarantee you'll spot a vibe in another booth that matches yours! All the dealers are crazy good vintage Christmas hunters. I hope to see you this weekend. I plan to be at the shop on Friday night! Come say hello!
#vintagejewelrychristmastree #vintagechristmasdecor #vintagechristmascollector #vintahechristmasornaments #vimtagechristmasdecorations #howihohoho

Christmas has arrived at @warehouse55_ I sometimes get grumpy about the retail season starting earlier and earlier. But it was a fun, festive week prepping for the big holiday event at the shop this weekend. I am not humble-bragging when I say, my space pales in comparison to the other spaces in the shop. They're all jam-packed with the tastiest vintage Christmas. All the dealers went alllllll out. When you come to the shop, plan for at least 2 hours. Maybe more. And bonus: we are open until 9 tonight! Alrighty... That's it for Christmas here until latish November. Signing off, your Vintage Christmas Elf.
#chicagovintageshop #vintagejewelrychristmastree #vintagechristmas #holidaycheer #holidaydecorating #vintaheholidaydecor #vintagejewelrychristmastree #vintahechristmasornaments #howihohoho #vintagechristmasshopping

I've decided that I'm tired of this stack of mirrors. I want to do something different on the front porch. Problem is, I don't know where to safely store these. They're fairly fragile. (Fyi...i want to keep them. Just want to put them away for a bit.) So here I sit, desiring change but immobilized. I think I want a statement piece on the front porch instead. Inevitably they will stay put for yet another year. I guess they are pretty if I stop and appreciate them. They're just a lot.. Too much. And I'm a much girl. That's saying something.
#antiquemirror #antiquemirrorcollection

This is what you call a late season garbage bouquet. I gathered the paltry remains of my garden, because frost is coming later in the week. A bouquet, even if it's garbage, id a great way to end a great weekend. Lots of house stuff. Some friend and family stuff. Some Warehouse 55 stuff. And lots of sleeping. Because last week killed me. I'm happy to say that I'm not beleaguered by the Sunday Scaries. I hope everyone has a great week!
#dahliabouquet #diyflowerarrangement #diybouquet #brasspeacock #vintagebrass

It's been a rough day. But found a quiet moment of beauty. 
#vignette #vintageglasssculpture #antiqueoilpainting

My husband is at an Ultimate tournament which has given me space to play around in the living room and dining room. I kept telling @jerome.at.home I was craving change. So after the dentist today, I made my son help me unroll this large antique rug that came out of an Indiana mansion. I love its fading. I love that it was only $150 even more. Then I picked up this Hollywood regency bench at Salvation Army. I'm smitten and can't wait to get it reupholstered by my upholsterer Luis. I need to find the perfect fabric, which is 85% of the fun--right? I  think I'll be replacing my current piano bench with this one.  It's a lotta gold in here. But I guess that's my signature. I might as well stick with it.
#tqitb #thequestisthebest
#vintagefurniture

Last night I came home from dinner with a friend and decided to paint all the trim and doors in the hallway the same green as the leaves (it happens to be the same color I've painted every single room in the house: Pinedale Shores by Behr). Depending on the light, the color shifts from blue to green, which I love. But I'm not sure I'm loving the painted trim. It's only the first coat. But I wonder if it's too dark or if I'm trying too hard or if...
 
I am headed out for the day, and I'll contemplate whether the white should return or if I should go forward with the second coat.
#vintageliving #handpaintedwall

It's been a hard week. But leave it to a creative pursuit to give you some emotional lift. It's my first Trunk or Treat at our church. I've been dreaming up the artist studio for the last 12 months. I reluctantly but dutifully restrained myself from pulling out the nudes. (This is a G-rated event after all.) I recently sold my old easel, so this morning I furiously hunted for one on FBM.  Lucky to have found it... and only 5 miles away. I always thought there should be an adult version of Trick or Treat called Trick or 'Tique (as in antique). Hope you all had a great weekend!

I'm glad you all weighed in on the green trim and were mostly pro-green!. I was definitely leaning towards going back to white (but, ugh, painting white over green would have taken forever!!!). I put on a second coat last night, and I think I'm liking it better. The rooms flow better. @jerome.at.home returns today, and I'm so glad that even if he does have a negative opinion, he won't make me change it. (Living with a creative is exhausting.)
#handpaintedwall #vintagebathroom #pursuepretty #livewithwhatyoulove #livedinstyle

I'm headed to PA to see my dear sister. While I wait to take off, I thought I'd share the alabaster birdbaths from a different perspective. It's an alabaster bash. While the weekend will be jam-packed, we'll see if I can sneak in an antique run or two. PA really has THE best questing. Though I hear Maine and NJ are bonkers, too. Happy Friday everyone!
#thequestisthebest #tqitb #alabastercollection #alabasterbirdbath

While I was in PA over the weekend, @jerome.at.home got busy rewiring chandeliers. I don't take for granted this act of service. It allows me to buy all the incredible lighting without the worry of rewiring service costs. That would get costly. Last May at @springfieldextrav I purchased this chandelier from one of my favorite dealers. It was in pieces--and it was fragile--which made me waffle. I wondered if it would even make it home safely. The guy then told me about where he purchased it, and the long journey it took to being discovered in a tub on the floor at an Ohio flea market, and I had to have it (he was a pretty good salesman.) This piece is everything: Murano glass and iron all twirled together as an art nouveau masterpiece. I keep walking around the house trying to figure out if I can find a fixture to swap and sell instead. Because really...I think this is one piece I would regret selling down the road.
#thequestisthebest #tqitb #flea#fleamarkeystyle #fleamarketshopping #fleamarketdecorating #oldchandelier #antiquelighting

I remember the first vintage bell I purchased as a twenty-something. I picked it up in Sumner, Washington at a favorite vintage shop. Little did I know that it would be the first of about 40. And while I will always have a special place in my heart for my first bell, my most recent bell from @meganmorrisonmoxie at @warehouse55_ is my new fave. I've never seen a multi-colored beaded bell. Usually, they come in one color--gold, green, blue, pink, red, or silver. This is my first Christmas decor to go up. She's a little lonely waiting for the bell choir to show up next week. But let's be honest, this gal is the diva of the bunch. The soprano. The star. The "ring"-leader. I'm delighted to add her to my ever-expanding collection. (And so darn excited to pull out my Christmas decor the day after Thanksgiving, since we will finally be home for the holiday!)
#vintagechristmasdecor #vintagechristmasornament #vintageholidaydecor #vintageornaments #vintagebellornaments #tqitb

For the past couple years I've wanted to change out my drapes. I have had them for about 21 years. I still love them--and will store them for a fresh look down the road. But I really wanted a pattern, specifically a floral. I found a custom drapery seller on eBay who specializes in drapes made of vintage fabrics. This chintz was a bold move for me. But I knew I needed something with pink in it. My husband thinks it looks like April in our living/dining room now. (And I think he may be right!) But I love the change, even if it continues to force me to make additional changes to the two rooms so it all makes sense (there still is too much brown in the furniture...sigh.) I keep reminding myself that I would have been so angry with myself if I went the safe route with a neutral and less punchy pattern. If you're interested in drapes, you might check out Artisan Draperies. As I mentioned yesterday, now that I have these colorful floral drapes, the brown upholstered furniture must be updated. (My husband will be thrilled.) Until then, I draped this antique silk textile over the chair.(I dyed it blue last summer.) It's all about slow decor over here. #slowdecor #chintzdrapes #mccoypottery #antiquesilk

Since we aren't in Colorado this year, I'm slowly taking out Christmas while not going all out until this Friday (I don't like feeling Christmasy at Thanksgiving. I like feeling Thanksgiving-y). Decking the halls with a few more pieces that can pass as Thanksgiving-ish. Last year I did something similar to my dining room chandelier. I tucked in some vintage picks and strung glass bird ornaments, so it looked like they were taking flight from a nest. This year I added to the nest--as all magpies do--tucking in some bedazzled vintage pinecones and more velvet fruit garland I painted gold and pink. Today, I'm focusing on the Thanksgiving table. I have a vision. I hope it comes to life!
#christmasdecoratingideas #christmasdecorideas #christmasdecorideas #deckthehalls #deckthehallswithdiy #vintagechristmas #vintagechristmasdecor #vintageholidaydecor

When I was a young mom, I was befriended by @jabtrc. She's an extraordinary artist, and I was pulled into her creative world. One of the many things I learned from Jill was the magic of RIT dye. She was fearless, always customizing fabric with the perfect blend of dye. I don't remember when I decided I should give it a go. But 22 plus years later, I'm still dyeing items (and turning my fingers the color of the dye bc I never slow down to put on gloves). This year I couldn't find the tablecloth I wanted to use, but remembered this crocheted tablecloth in the basement. I have a collection of them that I have dyed over the years. I wanted a color that would contrast with my new green plates, so I went bold with a wine color. That was in the back of my mind when I picked out flowers for the bouquet.  I really love how this table setting came together (even though we are still an hour away from stuffing ourselves). I'm grateful for Jill. She had such a huge influence on me, more than she'll ever know. I credit her for seeing my creative potential when I was so insecure in my 20s. I'm also grateful for each of you, also, who take time to share yourselves here with me and others. I think I have the best followers in the world. Always kind and encouraging. Thank you for being wonderful you. Happy Thanksgiving!
#thanksgivingtable #tablesetting #howihome #RITdye #creativejourney #decoratingwithvintage #livedinstyle #fleamarketstyle #propstylist

Somehow over the past year I've created quite a collection of mini vintage wreaths. I'm in the thick of Christmas decorating. And my muchness is manifesting. It's mania. Truly. I have too much for my small house. But I can't seem to muster any restraint. Stay tuned for some sneak peeks throughout the next couple days on Stories.
#vintageholiday #vintageholidaydecor #vintagechristmasdecoratingideas #vintagechristmas #holidayhome #christmascollection

The Christmas tree is complete. From this distance you can't appreciate the detail of the antique and vintage ornaments. Hundreds of Czech beaded ornaments. Hundreds of German glass ornaments. Decorating the tree takes forever, but it's joyful unwrapping all the ornaments you've forgotten. I'm also so pleased that this Chinese pot worked out for the Christmas tree. I bought it a few weekends ago when I was antiquing with a friend. I was on the fence--almost didn't purchase it, fearing it may be too large for the space. But it fits perfectly and grounds the tree (which is larger than years past). Who else is done with their decorating? I have a few odds and ends to wrap up. But I'm mostly done. On the first day of Christmas, my true love gave to me, a vintage flocked fruit garland. 

It's the first day of #tqitb (#thequestisthebest ) holiday edition. Every Monday, Wednesday and Friday for 4 weeks, we are marching through our interpretation of the 12 days of Christmas. Wednesday will be 2 of something. Friday will be 3 of something. Next Monday will be 4 of something. You get the idea 

Really there are no rules. I'll be posting holiday stuff, but you don't have to. Use the hashtag so other people can see your posts. And tag me so I can see it! 

I hope you enjoy the prompts. 

Back to my garland. I picked this up about 6 years ago when I was planning for the Flea Market Style holiday photo shoot. I found it in an antique mall. It was red, which isn't my color. So I bought some acrylic paint and changed the fruit to pink. I also sprayed the plastic leaves gold (they were green). Over the years I've added individual pieces of flocked fruit that I've found throughout the year. I paint it and tuck it in. It makes for one luxurious garland. Last year I didn't display it here. I've been doing a bit of thinking about "poetic interiors." I love poetry, for many reasons. The meaning wrapped up in symbols, similes and metaphors. Cadence--or rhythm--that emphasizes meaning and creates tone. Allusions referencing places, people, ideas. All of it--purposefully chosen to create a profound aesthetic experience. Often you feel a poem before you understand it; but the language invites you to linger. And it's in this lingering that you see yourself, the author, or the world around you a little more clearly. (My left-brained husband will probably be lost in the post.) A poetic home similarly invites others into a shared aesthetic--and deeply personal--experience. A poetic home is laced with symbols that evoke feelings. It purposefully repeats colors, pattern, textures, objects and themes. It's okay with a bit of dissonance, when objects, patterns or colors clash with purpose. When you're in a poetic home, you know the author of it. It's deeply personal. It's been crafted to evoke emotions, stimulate the imagination, and offer an experience beyond mere functionality. That's the type of home I want to live in, visit, and create.
